Scraping the web is one of the oldest job since the birth of the internet. This time, I will show you how to scrape, while also showing you how I got the data of **every** rooms in my campus (including empty ones) and their exact position in the floor they are in (using polygons).

# The Problem

My campus (Institut Teknologi Bandung) has already made an online directory of rooms, located on http://petakampus.itb.ac.id. But it's sluggish and requires Google Earth plugin (which is only available on Firefox and IE 32 bit (and not **Google** Chrome)). YAWN.

![](/content/images/2016/08/2016-08-12-221747_1366x768_scrot.png) Fig. 1

They even have the indoor maps using polygons as I said above.

![](/content/images/2016/08/72-Labtek-VI-Dapur.png) Fig. 2

# The Solution

First of all, here's a rule you should remember. *Everything that can be accessed via the browser, can be crawled.* We just need to know the structure of the data. Check everywhere, thoroughly.

## Step 1: Know Its Structure

Open the website (if you want to crawl a website) and view the source. `F12` in Chrome, for example. For some websites the data is available in plaintext inside the `<body>` tag.

![](/content/images/2016/08/2016-08-12-211724_1366x768_scrot.png) Fig. 3


But sometimes, website like `petakampus` uses a plugin (e.g Maps, Google Earth) which can not be crawled by plaintext.

![](/content/images/2016/08/2016-08-12-224151_1366x768_scrot.png) Fig. 4

You have to realize that the plugin **must** be initialized by something. Usually that something is a `<script>` inside the `<head>` tag.

![](/content/images/2016/08/2016-08-12-224752_1366x768_scrot.png) Fig. 5: Voila! Polygons!

## Step 2: Craft the Scraper

There are many tools to scrape with. We are going to use NodeJS tools since they have handy DOM selectors.

There's a fast and slim scraper named [`Osmosis`](https://github.com/rchipka/node-osmosis), and also the **HUGE** Electron-based scraper (can even screenshoot) [`Nightmare`](https://github.com/segmentio/nightmare). We will use the middleground for this one, the familiar [`Cheerio`](https://github.com/cheeriojs/cheerio).

We also need HTTP Client for this. I am choosing [`Axios`](https://github.com/mzabriskie/axios) since it is `Promise` based.

`$ npm i --save axios cheerio`

