*Asynchronous Functions. Callbacks. Promises.* **What the heck are these?** I asked myself that question several years ago, when I was still new to JavaScript. I came from the *nice, predictable,* and *Synchronous* world of embedded systems (think Arduino and low-level circuitry) and I was flabbergasted at first. I've since managed to understand the concept and now I will try to explain with simple examples to those who haven't.

# Pedagang Mie Keliling

![](/content/images/2016/08/bakso.jpeg)


Imagine a roving noodle stall. (Or those of you not familiar with these, imagine an Ice Cream Truck which serves the ice cream on plates, silverware included.) The stall has two methods, which are `findCustomers()` and `serveCustomers()`. 

`findCustomers()` move the stall 50m forward and generate noise to call customers, returning `true` if anyone comes. 

`serveCustomers()` makes it stop by a while to serve those customers (and those in the general area) and wait until the customers are finished to take back the plates and silverware.



And that, is our example application.

# Synchronous Code

If you are keen enough, maybe you can already see that most of those stalls operate synchronously. We'll try to put those in code terms.

```js
let isOpen = true
let customerFound = false

while (isOpen) {
  if (!customerFound) {
    customerFound = findCustomers()
  } else {
    serveCustomers()
    customerFound = false
  }
}
```

let me remind you that `findCustomers()` and `serveCustomers()` are both **sync** methods. Those of you familiar with Arduino might see the polling nature of the app resembles Arduino's `loop()` function.

First of all. This code **works**. It's good enough for the stalls. But **what if?** What if there's another customer, hungry for noodles, 100m ahead while the stall is in serving mode? That other customer would simply not get served until the current ones are finished. Tasks like these are called **blocking** or **synchronous**.

In an application UI (or browser) that behavior is not expected at all. We can't have our program go around the UI asking the question "has this button been clicked" (has the customers finished their meal) and "has this button been clicked" and so on. This ties up resources looping around the UI just checking in case something has happened. 

This isn't how most UI frameworks organize things. Instead they implement an event handling system. The user clicking a button is defined as an event and you can associate code with each event - the event handler. When the event occurs the event handler is run. 

This is such a familiar pattern that we hardy give it a second thought but you should. For example, suppose there are three buttons on the screen and the user clicks on all three at high speed - do three different event handlers get started? 

In most cases the answer is no, only one event handler is started at a time. The most common event handling architecture is single threaded - that is it only has one thread of execution and at any one time only one instruction in your entire program is being obeyed, which is analogous to our stall can only serve a customer at a time.

# Asynchronous Code

Synchronous functions are generally not a big problem because we have fast computers, and most event handlers are executed instantly.

But what about long-running tasks, like fetching data from third-party servers, and API calls? And for our stall, the serving part?

This is where **async** functions come in. While **sync** functions require our stall to wait until their completions, **async** tasks can be started and then put aside until later, while our stall proceeds to the next steps of the program.

Consider a function `asyncServeCustomers(callback)`.

```js
function asyncServeCustomers (cb) {
  makeAndGiveNoodleToCustomers()
  cb()
}
```

and we run it like this:

```js
let isOpen = true

function finishedEating () {
  // Call the stall to notify, or return the plates 
  // with drones, or whatever.
}

while (isOpen) {
  if (findCustomers()) {
    asyncsServeCustomers(finishedEating)
  }
}
```

Think of it like our stall serves the meal with a piece of paper with a link to trackable GPS coordinate of our stall (for the customers to return our plates) or at least a number to call to after they finish eating. Our driver can then stroll back down there and get the plates.

Now our stall can continue roving after it serves the meal to the customer, without having to wait for **those annoying customers who eat so damn slow** (like me) and serve other potential customers instead.

# Promises

> What about promises??

If youve done any serious work in JavaScript, you have probably had to face callbacks, nested inside of callbacks, nested inside of callbacks. 

![](/content/images/2016/08/promises-and-chaining-in-angularjs-into-callback-hell-and-back-again-17-638.jpg)

Promises, like callbacks, provide a way to deal with deferred work. (Returning the result of query to the client when it comes back from the database, or waiting the for customers to eat.) 

The main advantage of a promise over a callback is that you have an instance of an object that represents that deferred work. Let's say for example that you wanted to do two things in parallel after some asynchronous action. With callbacks, you would have to create a new callback that managed that flow. With promises, you can get a promise from the first action and pass it to methods that do the next action and get promises back.

It is not much different since in JavaScript, Promises use callback functions to specify what to do after a Promise has been resolved or rejected.

```js
function asyncServeCustomers (customer) {
  return new Promise(function (resolve, reject) {
    var noodle = new Noodle()
    noodle.onfinished = function () {
      resolve(customerLocation)
    }
    noodle.onerror = function () {
      reject(customerLocation)
    }
  })
}

```

Where `resolve` and `reject` are callbacks to handle async events.

```js
...
let curLoc = [LAT, LON]
...

  asyncServeCustomer(curLoc).then(function (location) {
    console.log(`customer in ${location} finished eating!`)
  }).catch(function (location) {
    console.log(`there's an error in customer ${location}!`)
  })
``` 
Regardless of the number of actions to process the `curLoc`, the level of callback functions used stays at one, which is a lot more maintainable and readable then using callback functions alone. 

I would say the biggest advantage is that it can lead to cleaner simpler code which is easier to test and maintain.


# Conclusion

And that is asynchronous code. There are many other resources which can explain it better than me but at least we can confirm here that the workflow of food stalls can learn a lot from Javascript.

There is still much to be explained, like Event Loop mentioned above, but it will be a subject for another post. Right now, I'm gonna enjoy my noodles.

